          "body": "After twenty-eight verses dominated by Solomon as the active subject, verse 29 makes the most important statement in the chapter with the fewest words: 'Now God gave Solomon wisdom.' The narrator will not allow the reader to credit Solomonic genius for Solomonic achievement. The wisdom is a gift — *chokhmah*, *tavunah*, *rochav lev* — comprehensive understanding in all its dimensions, given by the God who had promised it at Gibeon (1 Kings 3:12). This attribution is the chapter's theological climax, and it is placed deliberately after the administrative catalogue. The reader is meant to trace everything backward: the ordered court (4:2-6), the district system (4:7-19), the territorial peace (4:24-25), the international renown (4:34) — all flow from the divine gift of 4:29. Howard Hendricks would ask: 'Who is the ultimate actor in this chapter?' The answer comes 29 verses in: God. Solomonic glory is derivative glory. Its source is not human genius but divine generosity."
