          "body": "The final verses (4:29-34) describe a wisdom that is simultaneously divine in origin and encyclopedic in scope. Solomon spoke 3,000 proverbs and 1,005 songs — literary output identifying him as the fountainhead of Israel's canonical wisdom tradition (Proverbs 1:1; 10:1; Song of Solomon 1:1). His wisdom extended over the entire created order: trees from cedar to hyssop, animals, birds, reptiles, fish (4:33). This is proto-natural philosophy ordered under the fear of the LORD — wisdom that sees creation's order as God's order. The result: 'men came from all peoples to hear the wisdom of Solomon, from all the kings of the earth who had heard of his wisdom' (4:34). The nations are drawn not by military conquest but by wisdom. This is the centripetal vision of Isaiah 2:2-3 ('all the nations will stream to it') given a historical preview in Solomon's court. Jesus himself invokes this moment: 'the queen of the South... came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon, and behold, something greater than Solomon is here' (Matthew 12:42). The chapter points eschatologically to the One whose wisdom is not a divine gift administered through a fallible human vessel, but is itself divine — the eternal Logos, in whom 'are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Colossians 2:3)."
