        "number": 4,
        "title": "God gave — the divine source disclosed and the nations drawn in",
        "range": "4:29-34",
        "excerpt": "Now God gave Solomon wisdom and very great discernment and breadth of mind, like the sand that is on the seashore.",
        "body": "After twenty-eight verses in which Solomon is virtually the exclusive subject, verse 29 reassigns agency with the chapter's most theologically decisive sentence: *God gave Solomon wisdom.* The divine gift is then described in a triad — *chokhmah* (wisdom), *tavunah* (discernment), *rochav lev* (breadth of heart/mind). Each term adds a dimension. *Chokhmah* is skill in living rightly; *tavunah* is the analytical capacity to distinguish and discern; *rochav lev* — literally 'width of heart' — is the capacious, encyclopedic quality of understanding that refuses to be narrow. The measure of all three together: 'like the sand that is on the seashore' — the same Abrahamic image used in 4:20 for the population, now applied to the king's mind. The gift matches the nation.\n\nThe comparative benchmarks in 4:30-31 establish the magnitude of the gift by reference to the ancient world's recognized wisdom traditions. 'The wisdom of all the sons of the east' encompasses Mesopotamian, Arabian, and Chaldean sage-traditions — the wisdom-tradition of Babylon and Arabia that produced the book of Job's interlocutors and the Magi of the gospels. 'All the wisdom of Egypt' encompasses the scribal traditions of a civilization three millennia old. Solomon's wisdom exceeded both. Then the narrator names specific Israelite sages: Ethan the Ezrahite, Heman, Calcol, and Darda, sons of Mahol — sages associated with Psalm 88 (Heman) and Psalm 89 (Ethan) in the Psalter, figures whose reputation was apparently such that invoking their names as surpassed benchmarks carries rhetorical weight for the original audience.\n\nSolomon's wisdom expresses itself in three forms. Proverbs (*mashal*): 3,000 of them, the foundation of Israel's wisdom-literary tradition (Proverbs bears his name). Songs (*shir*): 1,005 — the Song of Songs canonized in Scripture. Natural wisdom (4:33): trees from cedar to hyssop, animals, birds, reptiles, fish — the entire created order observed, classified, and articulated. This is not encyclopedism for its own sake. It reflects the conviction that creation is ordered by the God whose wisdom pervades it, and that the wise person is one who reads creation's order as God's wisdom made visible. Calvin noted that all human learning, including natural science, is a gift of God's common grace — Solomon's encyclopedic natural wisdom is the royal embodiment of that principle.\n\nThe chapter's final verse (4:34) draws the chapter's argument to its conclusion and opens it outward: 'Men came from all peoples to hear the wisdom of Solomon, from all the kings of the earth who had heard of his wisdom.' The nations do not come as conquering armies to be repelled, nor as tribute-bearers under political compulsion — they come as students. The centripetal vision of Isaiah 2:2-3 ('all the nations will stream to it... that He may teach us concerning His ways') finds a provisional historical embodiment in Solomon's court. The queen of Sheba (1 Kings 10) is the narrative expansion of this one verse. And Jesus himself names this moment: 'the queen of the South will rise at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon, and behold, something greater than Solomon is here' (Matthew 12:42). The chapter that began with administrative machinery ends with an eschatological pointer.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chokhmah* (wisdom) — from a root meaning 'to be experienced, skilled'; *tavunah* (discernment) — from *bin*, to discern, distinguish, perceive; *rochav lev* — 'breadth of heart': *lev* is the Hebrew seat of intellect, will, and moral perception together. *Mashal* (proverb) — a comparative or figurative saying; also means 'to rule' (cf. 4:21, *mashal*) — the same root used for Solomon's dominion, a possible wordplay: the ruler who speaks *mashalim*."
